SIMPLE: piling
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Piling
<hw>Pil"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Pile</er> a
heap.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of heaping up.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Iron Manuf.)</fld> <def>The process of building up,
heating, and working, fagots, or piles, to form bars, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Piling</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Piling
<hw>Pil"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Pile</er> a stake.]</ety>
<def>A series of piles; piles considered collectively; <as>as, the
<ex>piling</ex> of a bridge</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pug piling</b></col>, <cd>sheet piles connected together
at the edges by dovetailed tongues and grooves.</cd> -- <col><b>Sheet
piling</b></col>, <cd>a series of piles made of planks or half logs
driven edge to edge, -- used to form the walls of cofferdams,
etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pill</ent>⟦br⟧
